Most founders say some version of: “Just make sure we don’t run out of money.”  
A bank reconciliation is how you turn that fear into 𝐜𝐚𝐬𝐡 𝐜𝐥𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐲.

A bank reconciliation compares two things:
– the bank’s record of cash
– your organization’s record of cash

If those two don’t match, every financial report you’re looking at is a guess.

Here’s why this matters:

• 𝐂𝐚𝐬𝐡 𝐜𝐥𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐲 — you know exactly how much money you have today
• 𝐄𝐫𝐫𝐨𝐫 𝐝𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 — missing transactions, duplicate payments, human error
• 𝐅𝐫𝐚𝐮𝐝 𝐝𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 — unauthorized withdrawals, altered checks, vendor issues
• 𝐎𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐚𝐥 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐢𝐩𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐞 — AP, AR, payroll, and deposits become timely
• 𝐑𝐞𝐩𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐠𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐲 — your P&L and balance sheet stop lying to you

If the bank rec isn’t done, nothing else in the financials can be trusted.

𝐂𝐫𝐚𝐰𝐥: do it monthly.
𝐖𝐚𝐥𝐤: have it done first business day each month.
𝐑𝐮𝐧: automate it (even if it's bank & accounting system exports to Excel).

A founder‑friendly translation:

“A bank reconciliation is how you prove your numbers are real.
If the cash isn’t reconciled, every decision you make is a guess.”

